In [14]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
wcss = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 
                    'k-means++', random_state = 42)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss)
plt.title('Elbow Graph')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

A k means clustering has been done for a better understaing of the features of the correlation between credit limit and balance and according to the graph that has been plotted the optimal number of clusters is 4

In [15]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, init = 'k-means++', random_state = 42)
y_kmeans = kmeans.fit_predict(X)
X = X.values
In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 8), dpi=80)
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 0, 0], X[y_kmeans == 0, 1], s = 100, c = 'red', label = 'Cluster 1')
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 1, 0], X[y_kmeans == 1, 1], s = 100, c = 'blue', label = 'Cluster 2')
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 2, 0], X[y_kmeans == 2, 1], s = 100, c = 'green', label = 'Cluster 3')
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 3, 0], X[y_kmeans == 3, 1], s = 100, c = 'cyan', label = 'Cluster 4')
plt.scatter(kmeans.cluster_centers_[:, 0], kmeans.cluster_centers_[:, 1], s = 200, c = 'yellow', label = 'Centroids')
plt.title('Clusters of customers')
plt.xlabel('Credit Limit')
plt.ylabel('Balance')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Analysis
(1) the first centroid(left to right) shows that the customers does not have much of a purchasing power because according to the graph both credit limit and the balance is low.Therefore the focus should not be given to this centroid.

(2) the second centroid focuses more on the customers that have a low credit limit and also their purchasing power is low but compared with the customers who are in the first centroid the customers that are in this second centroid are somewhat engaging.

(3) the third centroid focuses more on the customers with a high credit limit and a high balance,therefore it can be taken as the most valubale centroid. The customers in this category should be targeted with better offers to shop via credit cards because these customers are the most performing group out of the lot.

(4) the fourth and the final centroid falls under the customers that have a low balance but have a higher credit limit. Which goes to show that these customers should be retaned by giving engagement offers because they have been loyal.

In [18]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
wcss = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 'k-means++', random_state = 42)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss)
plt.title('The Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

A k means clustering has been done for a better understaing of the features of the correlation between purchases and payments and according to the graph that has been plotted the optimal number of clusters is 4

In [19]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, init = 'k-means++', random_state = 42)
y_kmeans = kmeans.fit_predict(X)
X = X.values
In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 8), dpi=80)
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 0, 0], X[y_kmeans == 0, 1], s = 100, c = 'red', label = 'Cluster 1')
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 1, 0], X[y_kmeans == 1, 1], s = 100, c = 'blue', label = 'Cluster 2')
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 2, 0], X[y_kmeans == 2, 1], s = 100, c = 'green', label = 'Cluster 3')
plt.scatter(X[y_kmeans == 3, 0], X[y_kmeans == 3, 1], s = 100, c = 'cyan', label = 'Cluster 4')
plt.scatter(kmeans.cluster_centers_[:, 0], kmeans.cluster_centers_[:, 1], s = 200, c = 'yellow', label = 'Centroids')
plt.title('Clusters of customers')
plt.xlabel('Payment')
plt.ylabel('Purchases')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Analysis
(1) the first centroid(left to right) shows customers where both the credit limit and the balance are low which then directly impacts on their purchasing power. (i.e low credit limit+low balance equals to a low purchasing power).Therefore the focus should not be given to this centroid.

(2) the second centroid focuses more on the customers who are more engaging that the customers that fall under the first centroid. Given that both their purchases and payments are low the customers that fall under this seconnd centroid does not have a high purchasing power. But this could be changed by giving the customers some special benifits in terms of a better credit limit or a discount(s). By doing so these customers can be pushed to the next class/centroid.

(3) the third centroid focuses more on the customers that have their payments low but with high purchases which infact make them the most valuable amoung all the centroids. The customers that fall under this category prefers to shop on offers and discounts and can be better targeted by discount/cashback coupons on their credit card usage.

(4) the fourth and the final centroid falls under the customers that pay more to purchase more and these customers should be retained by providing customer engagement benifits. These customers can be the most honest customers out of the whole bunch.
